<HEADLINE>
<P>
TODAY'S SCHEDULE FOR L.A. INTERNATIONAL FILM FESTIVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The American Film Institute Los Angeles International Film Festival opens today 
for two weeks at the Cineplex Odeon Century Plaza Cinemas. Here is today's 
schedule: 
</P>
<P>
'The Long Weekend (o' Despair)' 
</P>
<P>
United States, 1989, 93 minutes 
</P>
<P>
 8:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Bargain-basement Bret Easton Ellis: Six post-punk characters spend a dreary 
weekend whining about Angst and ennui, which they mispronounce. The film is a 
disaster technically: Some scenes are so dimly lit (and/or badly shot and/or 
stained from processing errors) that it's difficult to tell one character from 
another. Writer-producer-director Gregg Araki reportedly made this gritty 
exercise in self-indulgent alienation for $5,000; it looks like less. CHARLES 
SOLOMON 
</P>
</TEXT>
